In terms of sound design/music: holy FUCK. Some of the sound effects are pretty unconvincing, but they add nice background splashes of flavor to the text. But the /music/ is incredible. I had to sit on the menu screen for quite some time just to listen to the theme song—
In terms of art: this is a somewhat weak point in the game. The art is either really gorgeous or genuinely kind of janky, so it’s pretty hit-or-miss.

—what the hell is going on here.
In terms of gameplay: this will deter plenty of people, but there really isn’t any /gameplay/. You don’t even make choices in this game— it’s aaaaaalll reading, babeyyy.

Some of these memories are dreams that slip through your fingers like the fine, white sand of the beach. I’m only two hours in and it’s a very relaxing experience... but of course, these added memories add quite a hint of mystery, and I’m interested in getting to the bottom of—

—what’s real and what’s not. The game takes its sweet time, guiding you by the hand to witness the two main characters meeting as cute little five-year-olds, to going on a tropical vacation as twenty-one-year-olds. But some of the memories set out for you are... different.

In terms of storytelling (you know, what people play visual novels for), SeaBed is very unique. People have a hard time describing it, because it’s not a linear story. Instead, it’s a gently, painstakingly-woven web of memories— and it’s often hard to tell—

First, let’s talk shop. This game is usually $20, but I got it on sale for $13.39. Huzzah! The game is approximately 15-20 hours with multiple perspectives, and you can even unlock extra stories by playing through the main game. Plenty of bang for your buck.

Making this a review thread because it’s genuinely kinda hard finding proper reviews for this game?? Yeah. Anyways: “SeaBed” is a psychological mystery visual novel. And it is. SO gay. (And I absolutely love it.)
